cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.MM, cs.NE 

This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with video prediction, which is a common task in computer vision. The use of a novel architecture that is end-to-end learnable also suggests that it may belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a new approach to address the issue of high nonlinearity in the spatial domain, which could be relevant to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The use of experimental evaluations to compare the proposed approach to other widely used video prediction methods suggests that it may also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the use of frequency domain transformations to estimate and use the signal transformations suggests that it may belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
